          "text": "Let's start with **topic 1: relationship schema enrichment** since everything else (atomic updates, IDs, filenames) flows from decisions made here.\n\n---\n\n**The core question:** When you declare a `link` field in `types.yaml`, should the bidirectionality config live *on the owning field*, or in a *separate top-level `relations` section*?\n\nFor example, `goal.area` is a link from goal → area. If bidirectional, `area` should have a `goals` field pointing back. Where do you declare this contract?\n\n**Option A — inline on the field:**\n```yaml\ngoal:\n  fields:\n    area:\n      type: link\n      ref: area\n      bidirectional: true\n      inverse: goals    # field name on area\n```\n\n**Option B — separate top-level `relations` block:**\n```yaml\nrelations:\n  - from: goal\n    field: area\n    to: area\n    inverse: goals\n```\n\nOption A keeps everything about a field co-located with the field itself (easy to read per-type). Option B gives you a single place to see all cross-type relationships at a glance.\n\nWhich feels more natural to you when writing/reading `types.yaml`?",
